Simply checking if an order exists is **NOT** sufficient and creates a critical horizontal privilege escalation vulnerability. This pattern was exploited in the 2022 Optus breach where attackers enumerated through customer IDs to access 9.8 million records.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import java.util.Optional;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/orders")
public class OrderController {

    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository orderRepository;

    // VULNERABLE: No ownership verification!
    @GetMapping("/{orderId}")
    public Order getOrder(@PathVariable Long orderId) {
        Optional<Order> order = orderRepository.findById(orderId);

        if (order.isEmpty()) {
            throw new OrderNotFoundException("Order not found");
        }

        // Returns ANY user's order - horizontal privilege escalation!
        return order.get();
    }

    // VULNERABLE: Direct object reference without authorization
    @GetMapping("/invoice/{orderId}")
    public Invoice getInvoice(@PathVariable Long orderId) {
        return invoiceRepository.findByOrderId(orderId);
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Attacker enumerates order IDs to access other users' orders
for i in {1..10000}; do
  curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $ATTACKER_TOKEN" \
       "https://api.example.com/api/orders/$i" >> stolen_orders.json
done
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Any authenticated user can view any order by changing the ID
- Sequential/predictable IDs make enumeration trivial
- Exposes PII: names, addresses, payment info, purchase history
- Violates GDPR, PCI-DSS, and privacy regulations

**SECURE VERSION**:

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.security.core.annotation.AuthenticationPrincipal;
import org.springframework.security.access.AccessDeniedException;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import java.util.Optional;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/orders")
public class SecureOrderController {

    private static final Logger auditLog = LoggerFactory.getLogger("AUDIT");

    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository orderRepository;

    @GetMapping("/{orderId}")
    public Order getOrder(
            @PathVariable Long orderId,
            @AuthenticationPrincipal UserPrincipal currentUser) {

        Optional<Order> order = orderRepository.findById(orderId);

        if (order.isEmpty()) {
            auditLog.warn("Order lookup failed: orderId={}, userId={}", 
                         orderId, currentUser.getId());
            throw new OrderNotFoundException("Order not found");
        }

        // CRITICAL: Verify ownership before returning data
        if (!order.get().getUserId().equals(currentUser.getId())) {
            auditLog.error("UNAUTHORIZED ACCESS ATTEMPT: userId={} tried to access orderId={} owned by userId={}",
                          currentUser.getId(), orderId, order.get().getUserId());
            throw new AccessDeniedException("You do not have permission to view this order");
        }

        auditLog.info("Order accessed: orderId={}, userId={}", orderId, currentUser.getId());
        return order.get();
    }
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **Ownership verification**: Compares order's userId with authenticated user's ID before returning data
- **Audit logging**: Records all access attempts including unauthorized ones for incident response
- **Generic error messages**: Doesn't reveal whether order exists to unauthorized users

